  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">
      Given a Word MIME type (application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document) 
      and valid webUrl, FromMime returns "ms-word:ofe|u|{encoded-url}".
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">
      Given an Excel MIME type (application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet) 
      and valid webUrl, FromMime returns "ms-excel:ofe|u|{encoded-url}".
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">
      Given a PowerPoint MIME type (application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation) 
      and valid webUrl, FromMime returns "ms-powerpoint:ofe|u|{encoded-url}".
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">
      For unsupported MIME types (e.g., application/pdf), FromMime returns null.
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">
      For null or empty webUrl, FromMime returns null.
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">
      Unit tests exist and validate all MIME mappings, null handling, and edge cases.
    </criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All unit tests pass (dotnet test exits with code 0).</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    Reference spec.md Section 5.1 for the exact protocol URL format.
    
    MIME type constants to use:
    - Word: "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document"
    - Excel: "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet"  
    - PowerPoint: "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation"
    
    URL encoding is critical - use Uri.EscapeDataString() for the webUrl.
    
    Consider also supporting legacy MIME types:
    - application/msword (.doc)
    - application/vnd.ms-excel (.xls)
    - application/vnd.ms-powerpoint (.ppt)
  </notes>
